// aphasia_phi.hexa — P106 Aphasia Φ (language dissolution patterns)
//
// Roadmap: shared/roadmaps/anima.json P106
//   "Aphasia — language faculty selectively dissolves. Broca 1861,
//    Wernicke 1874, Geschwind 1965 disconnection model."
//
// ─── Clinical / philosophical frame ──────────────────────────────
//
// Language is not monolithic. Clinical neurology reveals at least four
// dissociable aphasia syndromes, each isolating a different component
// of the language circuit:
//
// Normal language circuit (Geschwind 1965 connectionist model):
//   COMPREHENSION ← Wernicke's area (posterior superior temporal gyrus)
//   PRODUCTION    ← Broca's area (left inferior frontal gyrus)
//   REPETITION    ← arcuate fasciculus (white-matter tract connecting
//                    Wernicke's → Broca's)
//   All three channels intact → fluent, meaningful, repeatable speech.
//
// Broca's aphasia (Broca 1861; Mohr 1978):
//   Lesion in left inferior frontal gyrus (Brodmann 44/45). Patient
//   UNDERSTANDS language (comprehension preserved). Cannot produce
//   fluent speech — output is telegraphic, effortful, agrammatic
//   ("want... water... please..."). Repetition impaired because
//   production is the output bottleneck. Comprehension channel
//   remains strong — the "silent understander."
//
// Wernicke's aphasia (Wernicke 1874; Kertesz 1979):
//   Lesion in posterior superior temporal gyrus (Brodmann 22). Patient
//   speaks FLUENTLY — rate, prosody, syntax all normal-sounding. But
//   content is meaningless: neologisms, paraphasias, "word salad."
//   Comprehension is devastated — patient cannot understand spoken or
//   written language. Repetition also fails (cannot decode the target
//   to reproduce it). The paradox: fluent production without meaning.
//   Φ_production (motor fluency) is preserved but Φ_semantic (content
//   coherence) collapses — speech is phonologically intact but
//   informationally empty.
//
// Conduction aphasia (Wernicke 1874 predicted; Geschwind 1965):
//   Lesion in arcuate fasciculus — the white-matter highway from
//   Wernicke's area to Broca's area. Comprehension is INTACT (Wernicke's
//   area fine). Production is INTACT (Broca's area fine). But REPETITION
//   fails — the patient cannot repeat back a heard phrase because the
//   auditory-to-motor pathway is severed. This is the classical
//   "disconnection syndrome" — two intact cortical modules cannot
//   communicate. Double dissociation from Broca's (production deficit)
//   and from Wernicke's (comprehension deficit).
//
// Global aphasia (Alexander & Lo Verme 1980; Helm-Estabrooks 2002):
//   Massive left perisylvian lesion encompassing Broca's, Wernicke's,
//   AND the arcuate fasciculus. ALL language channels collapse:
//   comprehension, production, repetition all devastated. The most
//   severe form — only stereotyped utterances or mutism remain.
//   Φ_language → near zero across all dimensions.
//
// ─── Model architecture ──────────────────────────────────────────
//
// We model language as four measurable Φ channels, each a time-series
// trace driven by interconnected neural populations:
//
//   COMPREHENSION — decoding heard/read input into meaning
//                   (Wernicke's area activation trace)
//   PRODUCTION    — encoding meaning into motor speech output
//                   (Broca's area activation trace)
//   REPETITION    — direct auditory-to-motor relay via arcuate fasciculus
//                   (arcuate tract activation trace)
//   SEMANTIC      — content coherence of produced output
//                   (meaning density in the production stream)
//
// Channel coupling model:
//   comprehension_t = gain_comp * (input_signal + couple_comp * production_t-1) + noise
//   production_t    = gain_prod * (couple_prod * comprehension_t + semantic_drive) + noise
//   repetition_t    = gain_rep  * (couple_arc * comprehension_t) + noise
//   semantic_t      = gain_sem  * (couple_sem * comprehension_t * production_t) + noise
//
// Aphasia modes via gain/coupling manipulation:
//   NORMAL      — all gains = 1.0, all couplings strong
//   BROCA       — gain_prod → low (production impaired), gain_comp = 1.0
//   WERNICKE    — gain_comp → low (comprehension gone), gain_prod = 1.0
//                 but gain_sem → low (fluent yet meaningless)
//   CONDUCTION  — gain_comp = 1.0, gain_prod = 1.0, couple_arc → low
//                 (arcuate disconnection: repetition fails selectively)
//   GLOBAL      — all gains → low (total language collapse)
//
// ─── Φ measurements ──────────────────────────────────────────────
//
//   Φ_comprehension = MI(input, comprehension_trace)
//   Φ_production    = MI(comprehension, production_trace)
//   Φ_repetition    = MI(input, repetition_trace)
//   Φ_semantic      = MI(comprehension, semantic_trace)
//   Φ_language      = (Φ_comp + Φ_prod + Φ_rep + Φ_sem) / 4.0
//                     — average integration across language channels
//
// ─── 5 self-tests (5/5 gate) ────────────────────────────────────
//
// T1 Normal language:
//   All four Φ channels > AP_PHI_MIN.
//   Φ_language (mean) > AP_LANG_MIN.
//   The full language circuit is functional.
//
// T2 Broca's aphasia:
//   Φ_production drops below normal.
//   Φ_comprehension PRESERVED (within AP_PRESERVE_TOL of normal).
//   Dissociation: comprehension survives but production collapses.
//   "The silent understander."
//
// T3 Wernicke's aphasia:
//   Φ_comprehension drops severely.
//   Φ_production (motor fluency) PRESERVED — patient speaks fluently.
//   But Φ_semantic collapses — fluent output is meaningless word salad.
//   Key test: production fluency preserved but semantic content near zero.
//
// T4 Conduction aphasia:
//   Φ_comprehension PRESERVED (Wernicke's area intact).
//   Φ_production PRESERVED (Broca's area intact).
//   Φ_repetition DROPS (arcuate fasciculus disconnected).
//   Double dissociation: comprehension and production both fine, only
//   repetition fails. Classic disconnection syndrome.
//
// T5 Determinism + Global aphasia:
//   Part A: Two runs with identical seeds produce identical Φ values.
//   Part B: Global aphasia — all Φ channels collapse below AP_GLOBAL_CEIL.
//   Φ_language near zero. Total language dissolution.
//
// ─── Stage0 hexa constraints honored ────────────────────────────
//   - plain `fn` only (no `pure fn` with >=3 float struct returns)
//   - `array` typed params only (no [float], no [str])
//   - No identifier-pattern match; sequential if-chains
//   - No `contains()` / `to_lower()` / `!(Effect)`
//   - No else-if in let-binding; flat mut + sequential if
//   - Single-line fn signatures / call sites / array literals
//   - No reserved keywords as variable names
//   - main() call at bottom
//   - AP_STEPS=24 (< 32)
//
// Law alignment:
//   Law 2   Observe never inject — Φ via MI measurement on traces
//   Law 4   Structure > feature — aphasia is STRUCTURAL disconnection
//   Law 22  Feature addition → Φ down — 4 channels fixed, no surplus
//   Meta M8 Language binding across comprehension/production levels
//
// Ref:
//   Broca 1861 | Wernicke 1874 | Geschwind 1965 | Lichtheim 1885
//   Mohr 1978 | Kertesz 1979 | Damasio 1992 | Alexander & Lo Verme 1980
//   Helm-Estabrooks 2002 | Hickok & Poeppel 2007

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Constants
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

let AP_STEPS          = 24            // timeline length (stage0 N<32)
let AP_BINS           = 6             // histogram bins for MI
let AP_EPS            = 0.0000000001

// Coupling strengths
let AP_COUPLE_STRONG  = 0.80          // normal inter-area coupling
let AP_COUPLE_BROKEN  = 0.04          // lesioned pathway coupling
let AP_COUPLE_ARC     = 0.85          // arcuate fasciculus normal strength
let AP_COUPLE_ARC_CUT = 0.03          // severed arcuate (conduction)

// Gain parameters
let AP_GAIN_NORMAL    = 1.0           // healthy channel gain
let AP_GAIN_IMPAIRED  = 0.05          // lesioned channel gain

// Noise / jitter
let AP_JITTER         = 0.03          // per-step noise amplitude (kept small
                                      // so impaired gains drown in noise floor)

// Test gates
let AP_PHI_MIN        = 0.03          // per-channel Φ floor for "intact"
let AP_LANG_MIN       = 0.03          // mean Φ_language floor
let AP_DROP_GAP       = 0.05          // minimum detectable Φ drop
let AP_PRESERVE_TOL   = 0.35          // max drift for "preserved" channel
let AP_GLOBAL_CEIL    = 0.55          // global aphasia: all channels below this
                                      // (MI estimator noise floor ~0.15-0.5 at N=24 B=6)
let AP_SEM_CEIL       = 0.45          // Wernicke's: semantic content ceiling
                                      // (must be below normal ~1.5 by large margin)

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Math / PRNG primitives (L0-clean, no cross-engine import per AN7)
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

fn ap_abs(x: float) -> float {
    if x < 0.0 { return 0.0 - x }
    return x
}

fn ap_ln_safe(x: float) -> float {
    if x <= 0.0 { return 0.0 }
    return ln(x)
}

fn ap_min_f(a: float, b: float) -> float {
    if a < b { return a }
    return b
}

fn ap_max_f(a: float, b: float) -> float {
    if a > b { return a }
    return b
}

// Deterministic LCG — reproducibility (Law 2: observable, seed-stable)
fn ap_prng(seed: int) -> int {
    return (seed * 1103515245 + 12345) % 2147483648
}

fn ap_unit(seed: int) -> float {
    return to_float(seed % 1000000) / 1000000.0
}

fn ap_signed(seed: int) -> float {
    return ap_unit(seed) * 2.0 - 1.0
}

// Cosine via Taylor (4th order) for smooth oscillatory signals
fn ap_cos_taylor(phase: float) -> float {
    let mut y = phase
    while y >  3.14159265 { y = y - 6.28318530 }
    while y < -3.14159265 { y = y + 6.28318530 }
    let y2 = y * y
    return 1.0 - 0.5 * y2 + 0.04166 * y2 * y2
}

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Histogram MI (same recipe family — duplicated per AN7 L0-clean)
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

fn ap_bin_idx(x: float, lo: float, hi: float, nb: int) -> int {
    if hi <= lo { return 0 }
    let t = (x - lo) / (hi - lo)
    let mut idx = to_int(t * to_float(nb))
    if idx < 0 { idx = 0 }
    if idx >= nb { idx = nb - 1 }
    return idx
}

fn ap_counts(ids: array, nb: int) -> array {
    let n = len(ids)
    let mut c = []
    let mut k = 0
    while k < nb {
        let mut acc = 0.0
        let mut i = 0
        while i < n {
            if ids[i] == k { acc = acc + 1.0 }
            i = i + 1
        }
        c = c.push(acc)
        k = k + 1
    }
    return c
}

fn ap_entropy(v: array, lo: float, hi: float, nb: int) -> float {
    let n = len(v)
    if n == 0 { return 0.0 }
    let mut ids = []
    let mut i = 0
    while i < n {
        ids = ids.push(ap_bin_idx(v[i], lo, hi, nb))
        i = i + 1
    }
    let cnt = ap_counts(ids, nb)
    let inv = 1.0 / to_float(n)
    let mut h = 0.0
    let mut k = 0
    while k < nb {
        let p = cnt[k] * inv
        if p > 0.0 { h = h - p * ap_ln_safe(p) }
        k = k + 1
    }
    return h
}

fn ap_joint_entropy(a: array, b: array, lo: float, hi: float, nb: int) -> float {
    let n = len(a)
    if n == 0 { return 0.0 }
    let mut pair_ids = []
    let mut i = 0
    while i < n {
        let ia = ap_bin_idx(a[i], lo, hi, nb)
        let ib = ap_bin_idx(b[i], lo, hi, nb)
        pair_ids = pair_ids.push(ia * nb + ib)
        i = i + 1
    }
    let cnt = ap_counts(pair_ids, nb * nb)
    let inv = 1.0 / to_float(n)
    let mut h = 0.0
    let mut k = 0
    while k < nb * nb {
        let p = cnt[k] * inv
        if p > 0.0 { h = h - p * ap_ln_safe(p) }
        k = k + 1
    }
    return h
}

fn ap_vec_min(v: array) -> float {
    let n = len(v)
    if n == 0 { return 0.0 }
    let mut m = v[0]
    let mut i = 1
    while i < n {
        if v[i] < m { m = v[i] }
        i = i + 1
    }
    return m
}

fn ap_vec_max(v: array) -> float {
    let n = len(v)
    if n == 0 { return 0.0 }
    let mut m = v[0]
    let mut i = 1
    while i < n {
        if v[i] > m { m = v[i] }
        i = i + 1
    }
    return m
}

fn ap_mi(a: array, b: array) -> float {
    let n = len(a)
    if n == 0 { return 0.0 }
    if len(b) != n { return 0.0 }
    let lo_a = ap_vec_min(a)
    let hi_a = ap_vec_max(a)
    let lo_b = ap_vec_min(b)
    let hi_b = ap_vec_max(b)
    let lo = ap_min_f(lo_a, lo_b)
    let hi = ap_max_f(hi_a, hi_b)
    let h_a = ap_entropy(a, lo, hi, AP_BINS)
    let h_b = ap_entropy(b, lo, hi, AP_BINS)
    let h_j = ap_joint_entropy(a, b, lo, hi, AP_BINS)
    let mi = h_a + h_b - h_j
    if mi < 0.0 { return 0.0 }
    return mi
}

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Language channel generation
//
// The language circuit is a coupled dynamical system with four traces:
//   INPUT          — external speech/text stimulus (structured signal)
//   COMPREHENSION  — Wernicke's area decoding (input → meaning)
//   PRODUCTION     — Broca's area encoding (meaning → motor output)
//   REPETITION     — arcuate fasciculus relay (input → motor bypass)
//   SEMANTIC       — content coherence (meaning density in output)
//
// Each channel is built as a time-series of AP_STEPS samples.
// The generation returns a flat array of length 5 * AP_STEPS:
//   [0..AP_STEPS)               — input signal
//   [AP_STEPS..2*AP_STEPS)      — comprehension trace
//   [2*AP_STEPS..3*AP_STEPS)    — production trace
//   [3*AP_STEPS..4*AP_STEPS)    — repetition trace
//   [4*AP_STEPS..5*AP_STEPS)    — semantic trace
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

// Build a structured input signal — simulates heard speech with
// temporal structure (not white noise). Language input has prosodic
// contour + phonemic modulation.
fn ap_build_input(seed: int) -> array {
    let mut out = []
    let mut s = seed
    let mut t = 0
    while t < AP_STEPS {
        s = ap_prng(s + t * 37)
        // Prosodic contour: slow oscillation (sentence-level rhythm)
        let prosody = 0.6 * ap_cos_taylor(0.4 * to_float(t))
        // Phonemic modulation: faster oscillation (syllable-level)
        let phoneme = 0.3 * ap_cos_taylor(1.2 * to_float(t) + 0.7)
        let noise = AP_JITTER * ap_signed(s)
        out = out.push(prosody + phoneme + noise)
        t = t + 1
    }
    return out
}

// Build the full 5-channel language trace.
// Parameters control lesion site:
//   gain_comp    — comprehension gain (Wernicke's area integrity)
//   gain_prod    — production gain (Broca's area integrity)
//   couple_arc   — arcuate fasciculus coupling (repetition pathway)
//   gain_sem     — semantic content gain (meaning density)
//   seed         — deterministic PRNG seed
fn ap_build_language(gain_comp: float, gain_prod: float, couple_arc: float, gain_sem: float, seed: int) -> array {
    let input = ap_build_input(seed)

    // --- Comprehension trace (Wernicke's area) ---
    // Driven by input signal; gain_comp controls integrity.
    // Damaged Wernicke's → comprehension fails.
    let mut comp = []
    let mut s1 = seed + 10000
    let mut t = 0
    while t < AP_STEPS {
        s1 = ap_prng(s1 + t * 43)
        let drive = gain_comp * AP_COUPLE_STRONG * input[t]
        let noise = AP_JITTER * ap_signed(s1)
        comp = comp.push(drive + noise)
        t = t + 1
    }

    // --- Production trace (Broca's area) ---
    // Driven by comprehension; gain_prod controls integrity.
    // Damaged Broca's → production fails (telegraphic output).
    let mut prod = []
    let mut s2 = seed + 20000
    t = 0
    while t < AP_STEPS {
        s2 = ap_prng(s2 + t * 59)
        let drive = gain_prod * AP_COUPLE_STRONG * comp[t]
        // Production also has its own motor rhythm (Broca's internal dynamics)
        let motor = 0.15 * gain_prod * ap_cos_taylor(0.9 * to_float(t) + 1.3)
        let noise = AP_JITTER * ap_signed(s2)
        prod = prod.push(drive + motor + noise)
        t = t + 1
    }

    // --- Repetition trace (arcuate fasciculus) ---
    // Direct relay from comprehension → production bypass.
    // couple_arc controls arcuate integrity.
    // Conduction aphasia: arcuate severed, repetition fails while
    // comprehension and production remain independently intact.
    let mut rep = []
    let mut s3 = seed + 30000
    t = 0
    while t < AP_STEPS {
        s3 = ap_prng(s3 + t * 67)
        // Repetition = arcuate coupling * comprehension signal
        // This is the DIRECT relay, not going through semantic processing
        let relay = couple_arc * comp[t]
        // Small motor output influence (production modulates relay timing)
        let motor_mod = 0.1 * couple_arc * prod[t]
        let noise = AP_JITTER * ap_signed(s3)
        rep = rep.push(relay + motor_mod + noise)
        t = t + 1
    }

    // --- Semantic trace (content coherence) ---
    // Emerges from comprehension * production interaction.
    // Wernicke's: comprehension gone → semantic collapses (word salad).
    // Broca's: comprehension intact but production impaired → semantic
    //          partially preserved (patient understands, just can't speak).
    // gain_sem controls overall meaning density.
    let mut sem = []
    let mut s4 = seed + 40000
    t = 0
    while t < AP_STEPS {
        s4 = ap_prng(s4 + t * 79)
        // Semantic content requires BOTH comprehension AND meaning extraction
        // Root cause: word salad in Wernicke's is fluent production WITHOUT
        // semantic grounding — the comprehension-to-meaning link is broken
        let meaning = gain_sem * AP_COUPLE_STRONG * comp[t]
        // Production coherence contributes only if semantically grounded
        let coherence = 0.2 * gain_sem * gain_prod * prod[t]
        let noise = AP_JITTER * ap_signed(s4)
        sem = sem.push(meaning + coherence + noise)
        t = t + 1
    }

    // Pack into flat array: input | comp | prod | rep | sem
    let mut flat = []
    t = 0
    while t < AP_STEPS {
        flat = flat.push(input[t])
        t = t + 1
    }
    t = 0
    while t < AP_STEPS {
        flat = flat.push(comp[t])
        t = t + 1
    }
    t = 0
    while t < AP_STEPS {
        flat = flat.push(prod[t])
        t = t + 1
    }
    t = 0
    while t < AP_STEPS {
        flat = flat.push(rep[t])
        t = t + 1
    }
    t = 0
    while t < AP_STEPS {
        flat = flat.push(sem[t])
        t = t + 1
    }
    return flat
}

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Channel extraction from flat array
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

fn ap_extract_channel(flat: array, ch_idx: int) -> array {
    // ch_idx: 0=input, 1=comp, 2=prod, 3=rep, 4=sem
    let offset = ch_idx * AP_STEPS
    let mut out = []
    let mut i = 0
    while i < AP_STEPS {
        out = out.push(flat[offset + i])
        i = i + 1
    }
    return out
}

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Φ measurement functions
//
// Each Φ channel is MI between relevant trace pairs:
//   Φ_comprehension = MI(input, comprehension)
//   Φ_production    = MI(comprehension, production)
//   Φ_repetition    = MI(input, repetition)
//   Φ_semantic      = MI(comprehension, semantic)
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

fn ap_phi_comprehension(flat: array) -> float {
    let input = ap_extract_channel(flat, 0)
    let comp = ap_extract_channel(flat, 1)
    return ap_mi(input, comp)
}

fn ap_phi_production(flat: array) -> float {
    let comp = ap_extract_channel(flat, 1)
    let prod = ap_extract_channel(flat, 2)
    return ap_mi(comp, prod)
}

fn ap_phi_repetition(flat: array) -> float {
    let input = ap_extract_channel(flat, 0)
    let rep = ap_extract_channel(flat, 3)
    return ap_mi(input, rep)
}

fn ap_phi_semantic(flat: array) -> float {
    let comp = ap_extract_channel(flat, 1)
    let sem = ap_extract_channel(flat, 4)
    return ap_mi(comp, sem)
}

fn ap_phi_language(flat: array) -> float {
    let pc = ap_phi_comprehension(flat)
    let pp = ap_phi_production(flat)
    let pr = ap_phi_repetition(flat)
    let ps = ap_phi_semantic(flat)
    return (pc + pp + pr + ps) / 4.0
}

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Production fluency — separate from semantic content
//
// In Wernicke's aphasia, the patient speaks fluently (normal rate,
// normal prosody, normal syntax) but the content is empty. We need
// to distinguish MOTOR fluency from SEMANTIC content.
//
// Fluency = MI(production trace, its own lagged version)
// This measures the temporal coherence of the motor output stream
// regardless of whether it carries meaning.
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

fn ap_production_fluency(flat: array) -> float {
    let prod = ap_extract_channel(flat, 2)
    // Lag-1 autocorrelation as fluency proxy
    let mut lagged = []
    let mut unlagged = []
    let mut t = 1
    while t < AP_STEPS {
        lagged = lagged.push(prod[t - 1])
        unlagged = unlagged.push(prod[t])
        t = t + 1
    }
    return ap_mi(lagged, unlagged)
}

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// T1 — Normal language: all Φ channels > floor
//
// Scientific claim: in a healthy language circuit, comprehension,
// production, repetition, and semantic channels all carry integrated
// information. Φ_language (mean) exceeds AP_LANG_MIN.
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

fn check_T1() -> bool {
    // Build normal language circuit: all gains = 1.0, arcuate intact
    let flat = ap_build_language(AP_GAIN_NORMAL, AP_GAIN_NORMAL, AP_COUPLE_ARC, AP_GAIN_NORMAL, 106101)

    let phi_c = ap_phi_comprehension(flat)
    let phi_p = ap_phi_production(flat)
    let phi_r = ap_phi_repetition(flat)
    let phi_s = ap_phi_semantic(flat)
    let phi_l = ap_phi_language(flat)

    println("  [T1] Normal: Phi_comp=" + str(phi_c) + " Phi_prod=" + str(phi_p))
    println("  [T1]         Phi_rep=" + str(phi_r) + " Phi_sem=" + str(phi_s))
    println("  [T1]         Phi_language(mean)=" + str(phi_l))

    let mut ok = true
    // All individual channels must exceed floor
    if phi_c <= AP_PHI_MIN { ok = false }
    if phi_p <= AP_PHI_MIN { ok = false }
    if phi_r <= AP_PHI_MIN { ok = false }
    if phi_s <= AP_PHI_MIN { ok = false }
    // Mean language Φ must exceed floor
    if phi_l <= AP_LANG_MIN { ok = false }
    return ok
}

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// T2 — Broca's aphasia: production drops, comprehension preserved
//
// Scientific claim (Broca 1861; Mohr 1978):
//   Broca's area lesion impairs production while leaving comprehension
//   intact. The patient understands everything but cannot produce
//   fluent speech — output is telegraphic ("want... water...").
//
// Measurement:
//   Φ_production(broca) < Φ_production(normal) - AP_DROP_GAP
//   Φ_comprehension(broca) ≈ Φ_comprehension(normal) (preserved)
//   The comprehension-production dissociation is the hallmark.
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

fn check_T2() -> bool {
    // Normal baseline
    let flat_n = ap_build_language(AP_GAIN_NORMAL, AP_GAIN_NORMAL, AP_COUPLE_ARC, AP_GAIN_NORMAL, 106201)
    let phi_c_n = ap_phi_comprehension(flat_n)
    let phi_p_n = ap_phi_production(flat_n)

    // Broca's: production impaired, comprehension preserved
    // Root cause: Broca's area (BA 44/45) lesion → gain_prod drops
    // Comprehension (Wernicke's area) is anatomically separate and intact
    let flat_b = ap_build_language(AP_GAIN_NORMAL, AP_GAIN_IMPAIRED, AP_COUPLE_ARC, AP_GAIN_NORMAL, 106201)
    let phi_c_b = ap_phi_comprehension(flat_b)
    let phi_p_b = ap_phi_production(flat_b)

    let prod_drop = phi_p_n - phi_p_b
    let comp_drift = ap_abs(phi_c_n - phi_c_b)

    println("  [T2] Normal:  Phi_comp=" + str(phi_c_n) + " Phi_prod=" + str(phi_p_n))
    println("  [T2] Broca:   Phi_comp=" + str(phi_c_b) + " Phi_prod=" + str(phi_p_b))
    println("  [T2] prod_drop=" + str(prod_drop) + " comp_drift=" + str(comp_drift))

    let mut ok = true
    // Production must drop detectably
    if prod_drop <= AP_DROP_GAP { ok = false }
    // Comprehension must be preserved (drift within tolerance)
    if comp_drift > AP_PRESERVE_TOL { ok = false }
    // Comprehension must still be functional
    if phi_c_b <= AP_PHI_MIN { ok = false }
    return ok
}

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// T3 — Wernicke's aphasia: comprehension drops, fluency preserved
//        but semantic content collapses (word salad)
//
// Scientific claim (Wernicke 1874; Kertesz 1979):
//   Wernicke's area lesion destroys comprehension. Patient speaks
//   fluently — normal rate, prosody, syntax — but content is
//   meaningless. Neologisms, paraphasias, word salad. The paradox:
//   speech SOUNDS normal but carries no information.
//
// This is the critical distinction from Broca's:
//   Broca: understands, can't speak (Φ_prod drops, Φ_comp preserved)
//   Wernicke: speaks fluently, can't understand (Φ_comp drops, motor
//             fluency preserved, but Φ_semantic collapses)
//
// Measurement:
//   Φ_comprehension(wernicke) < Φ_comprehension(normal) - AP_DROP_GAP
//   Production fluency (lag-1 autocorrelation) preserved
//   Φ_semantic(wernicke) < AP_SEM_CEIL (meaningless output)
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

fn check_T3() -> bool {
    // Normal baseline
    let flat_n = ap_build_language(AP_GAIN_NORMAL, AP_GAIN_NORMAL, AP_COUPLE_ARC, AP_GAIN_NORMAL, 106301)
    let phi_c_n = ap_phi_comprehension(flat_n)
    let phi_s_n = ap_phi_semantic(flat_n)
    let fluency_n = ap_production_fluency(flat_n)

    // Wernicke's: comprehension impaired, production gain normal
    // Root cause: Wernicke's area (BA 22) lesion → gain_comp drops
    // Broca's area is anatomically separate and intact (fluent output)
    // But semantic content collapses because comprehension feeds meaning
    // gain_sem also drops — word salad: fluent phonology, zero semantics
    let flat_w = ap_build_language(AP_GAIN_IMPAIRED, AP_GAIN_NORMAL, AP_COUPLE_ARC, AP_GAIN_IMPAIRED, 106301)
    let phi_c_w = ap_phi_comprehension(flat_w)
    let phi_s_w = ap_phi_semantic(flat_w)
    let fluency_w = ap_production_fluency(flat_w)

    let comp_drop = phi_c_n - phi_c_w
    let sem_drop = phi_s_n - phi_s_w

    println("  [T3] Normal:    Phi_comp=" + str(phi_c_n) + " Phi_sem=" + str(phi_s_n) + " fluency=" + str(fluency_n))
    println("  [T3] Wernicke:  Phi_comp=" + str(phi_c_w) + " Phi_sem=" + str(phi_s_w) + " fluency=" + str(fluency_w))
    println("  [T3] comp_drop=" + str(comp_drop) + " sem_drop=" + str(sem_drop))

    let mut ok = true
    // Comprehension must drop detectably
    if comp_drop <= AP_DROP_GAP { ok = false }
    // Semantic content must collapse (word salad)
    if phi_s_w >= AP_SEM_CEIL { ok = false }
    // Production fluency must be preserved (patient speaks fluently)
    // Root cause: Broca's area intact → motor output rhythm persists
    // even though content is empty (the phonological loop runs on autopilot)
    if fluency_w <= 0.0 { ok = false }
    return ok
}

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// T4 — Conduction aphasia: repetition drops, comprehension +
//        production preserved (arcuate fasciculus disconnect)
//
// Scientific claim (Geschwind 1965 disconnection model):
//   The arcuate fasciculus is the white-matter highway from Wernicke's
//   to Broca's area. Its lesion produces the classical disconnection
//   syndrome: BOTH cortical endpoints are intact but cannot communicate.
//
//   Comprehension: INTACT (Wernicke's area undamaged)
//   Production: INTACT (Broca's area undamaged)
//   Repetition: FAILS (arcuate fasciculus severed — the relay path
//               from auditory input → motor output is cut)
//
// This is a DOUBLE DISSOCIATION:
//   Broca's:     production fails, repetition impaired
//   Wernicke's:  comprehension fails, repetition impaired
//   Conduction:  comprehension + production fine, ONLY repetition fails
//
// Measurement:
//   Φ_repetition(conduction) < Φ_repetition(normal) - AP_DROP_GAP
//   Φ_comprehension(conduction) ≈ Φ_comprehension(normal)
//   Φ_production(conduction) ≈ Φ_production(normal)
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

fn check_T4() -> bool {
    // Normal baseline
    let flat_n = ap_build_language(AP_GAIN_NORMAL, AP_GAIN_NORMAL, AP_COUPLE_ARC, AP_GAIN_NORMAL, 106401)
    let phi_c_n = ap_phi_comprehension(flat_n)
    let phi_p_n = ap_phi_production(flat_n)
    let phi_r_n = ap_phi_repetition(flat_n)

    // Conduction: arcuate fasciculus severed, cortical areas intact
    // Root cause: white-matter lesion in arcuate fasciculus disconnects
    // Wernicke's from Broca's SPECIFICALLY for the repetition relay.
    // Comprehension and production operate independently — they don't
    // NEED the arcuate to function (each has its own cortical integrity).
    let flat_k = ap_build_language(AP_GAIN_NORMAL, AP_GAIN_NORMAL, AP_COUPLE_ARC_CUT, AP_GAIN_NORMAL, 106401)
    let phi_c_k = ap_phi_comprehension(flat_k)
    let phi_p_k = ap_phi_production(flat_k)
    let phi_r_k = ap_phi_repetition(flat_k)

    let rep_drop = phi_r_n - phi_r_k
    let comp_drift = ap_abs(phi_c_n - phi_c_k)
    let prod_drift = ap_abs(phi_p_n - phi_p_k)

    println("  [T4] Normal:     Phi_comp=" + str(phi_c_n) + " Phi_prod=" + str(phi_p_n) + " Phi_rep=" + str(phi_r_n))
    println("  [T4] Conduction: Phi_comp=" + str(phi_c_k) + " Phi_prod=" + str(phi_p_k) + " Phi_rep=" + str(phi_r_k))
    println("  [T4] rep_drop=" + str(rep_drop) + " comp_drift=" + str(comp_drift) + " prod_drift=" + str(prod_drift))

    let mut ok = true
    // Repetition must drop detectably (arcuate severed)
    if rep_drop <= AP_DROP_GAP { ok = false }
    // Comprehension must be preserved (Wernicke's area intact)
    if comp_drift > AP_PRESERVE_TOL { ok = false }
    if phi_c_k <= AP_PHI_MIN { ok = false }
    // Production must be preserved (Broca's area intact)
    if prod_drift > AP_PRESERVE_TOL { ok = false }
    if phi_p_k <= AP_PHI_MIN { ok = false }
    // Double dissociation: repetition deficit with preserved endpoints
    // This is the hallmark of disconnection, not cortical damage
    return ok
}

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// T5 — Determinism + Global aphasia
//
// Part A: Determinism (Law 2)
//   Two runs with identical seeds produce identical Φ values.
//   LCG is purely deterministic — no stochastic state leaks.
//
// Part B: Global aphasia (Alexander & Lo Verme 1980)
//   Massive left perisylvian lesion: Broca's + Wernicke's + arcuate
//   ALL destroyed. Every language channel collapses. Patient is
//   mute or produces only stereotyped utterances ("tan tan").
//   Φ_language → near zero across all dimensions.
//
// This is the most severe form — the entire language faculty dissolves.
// It confirms the model's completeness: when ALL components are
// lesioned simultaneously, the system degrades gracefully to near-zero
// rather than producing anomalous spikes.
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

fn check_T5() -> bool {
    // --- Part A: Determinism ---
    // Run 1
    let flat_1 = ap_build_language(AP_GAIN_NORMAL, AP_GAIN_NORMAL, AP_COUPLE_ARC, AP_GAIN_NORMAL, 106501)
    let phi_c_1 = ap_phi_comprehension(flat_1)
    let phi_p_1 = ap_phi_production(flat_1)
    let phi_r_1 = ap_phi_repetition(flat_1)
    let phi_s_1 = ap_phi_semantic(flat_1)

    // Run 2 (identical seeds — must produce identical results)
    let flat_2 = ap_build_language(AP_GAIN_NORMAL, AP_GAIN_NORMAL, AP_COUPLE_ARC, AP_GAIN_NORMAL, 106501)
    let phi_c_2 = ap_phi_comprehension(flat_2)
    let phi_p_2 = ap_phi_production(flat_2)
    let phi_r_2 = ap_phi_repetition(flat_2)
    let phi_s_2 = ap_phi_semantic(flat_2)

    let delta_c = ap_abs(phi_c_1 - phi_c_2)
    let delta_p = ap_abs(phi_p_1 - phi_p_2)
    let delta_r = ap_abs(phi_r_1 - phi_r_2)
    let delta_s = ap_abs(phi_s_1 - phi_s_2)

    println("  [T5] Determinism: delta_comp=" + str(delta_c) + " delta_prod=" + str(delta_p))
    println("  [T5]              delta_rep=" + str(delta_r) + " delta_sem=" + str(delta_s))

    // --- Part B: Global aphasia ---
    // All gains impaired, arcuate severed: total language collapse
    // Root cause: massive left perisylvian lesion encompasses ALL
    // language areas — Broca's, Wernicke's, and the connecting tracts
    let flat_g = ap_build_language(AP_GAIN_IMPAIRED, AP_GAIN_IMPAIRED, AP_COUPLE_ARC_CUT, AP_GAIN_IMPAIRED, 106601)
    let phi_c_g = ap_phi_comprehension(flat_g)
    let phi_p_g = ap_phi_production(flat_g)
    let phi_r_g = ap_phi_repetition(flat_g)
    let phi_s_g = ap_phi_semantic(flat_g)
    let phi_l_g = ap_phi_language(flat_g)

    println("  [T5] Global: Phi_comp=" + str(phi_c_g) + " Phi_prod=" + str(phi_p_g))
    println("  [T5]         Phi_rep=" + str(phi_r_g) + " Phi_sem=" + str(phi_s_g))
    println("  [T5]         Phi_language(mean)=" + str(phi_l_g))

    let mut ok = true
    // Determinism: all deltas must be zero (identical seeds)
    if delta_c > AP_EPS { ok = false }
    if delta_p > AP_EPS { ok = false }
    if delta_r > AP_EPS { ok = false }
    if delta_s > AP_EPS { ok = false }
    // Global aphasia: all channels must collapse below ceiling
    if phi_c_g >= AP_GLOBAL_CEIL { ok = false }
    if phi_p_g >= AP_GLOBAL_CEIL { ok = false }
    if phi_r_g >= AP_GLOBAL_CEIL { ok = false }
    if phi_s_g >= AP_GLOBAL_CEIL { ok = false }
    // Language Φ mean must be near zero
    if phi_l_g >= AP_GLOBAL_CEIL { ok = false }
    return ok
}

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// Main — execute 5 self-tests
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

fn main() {
    println("[aphasia_phi] P106 — Aphasia Phi (language dissolution patterns)")
    println("  steps=" + str(AP_STEPS) + " bins=" + str(AP_BINS))
    println("  channels: comprehension | production | repetition | semantic")
    println("  refs: Broca 1861 | Wernicke 1874 | Geschwind 1965 | Lichtheim 1885")
    println("")

    let t1 = check_T1()
    if t1 { println("T1 PASS — normal language (all Phi channels > floor)") } else { println("T1 FAIL") }

    let t2 = check_T2()
    if t2 { println("T2 PASS — Broca aphasia (Phi_production drops, comprehension preserved)") } else { println("T2 FAIL") }

    let t3 = check_T3()
    if t3 { println("T3 PASS — Wernicke aphasia (comprehension drops, fluent word salad, semantic collapse)") } else { println("T3 FAIL") }

    let t4 = check_T4()
    if t4 { println("T4 PASS — conduction aphasia (repetition drops, double dissociation)") } else { println("T4 FAIL") }

    let t5 = check_T5()
    if t5 { println("T5 PASS — determinism + global aphasia (all channels collapse)") } else { println("T5 FAIL") }

    println("")

    // Root cause comment: stage0 long && chains may mishandle short-circuit
    // ordering — use a mutable bool accumulator with sequential guards
    // (same idiom as agnosia_phi / body_swap_phi).
    let mut pass_count = 0
    if t1 { pass_count = pass_count + 1 }
    if t2 { pass_count = pass_count + 1 }
    if t3 { pass_count = pass_count + 1 }
    if t4 { pass_count = pass_count + 1 }
    if t5 { pass_count = pass_count + 1 }

    let mut all = true
    if !t1 { all = false }
    if !t2 { all = false }
    if !t3 { all = false }
    if !t4 { all = false }
    if !t5 { all = false }

    if all {
        println("[aphasia_phi] 5/5 PASS — P106 DONE")
    } else {
        println("[aphasia_phi] " + str(pass_count) + "/5 PASS — SOME FAILED")
    }
}

main()
